column113: There is general availability of the vaccine to people 12 and older. It is still noted that those people who have an increased risk of severe or fatal courses of a COVID-19 disease, for example due to old age or certain pre-existing conditions, received a vaccination [prioritized] offer. Furthermore, this included groups of people who are either particularly exposed professionally or have close contacts of vulnerable groups of people – for example, medical staff or nurses. The prioritization was introduced with a new version of the Coronavirus Vaccination Ordinance as of June 7, 2021, as most people in the prioritization groups had received a vaccination offer in the meantime. In the meantime, all citizens aged 12 and over can arrange a vaccination appointment. https://web.archive.org/web/20220128160650/https://www.zusammengegencorona.de/impfen/basiswissen-zum-impfen/die-nationale-impfstrategie/

column113: National Vaccination Strategy was and is the basis for this. Among other things, it outlines the fair distribution of corona vaccines and the organization of the COVID-19 vaccination campaign in different phases and prioritizations: In the first phase, people at high risk and exposed parts of the population could be vaccinated – mainly in vaccination centers or by mobile vaccination teams. On 7 June 2021, vaccination priority was lifted in Germany. https://web.archive.org/web/20220207150507/https://www.zusammengegencorona.de/impfen/basiswissen-zum-impfen/die-nationale-impfstrategie/

column72: For small and medium-sized businesses, the self-employed and non-profit organizations, there is a bridging aid for sales declines during the coronavirus pandemic. In addition, newly founded companies that are less than five years old can make corona relief loans. In addition, newly founded companies that are less than five years old can make corona relief loans  https://web.archive.org/web/20220207150507/https://www.zusammengegencorona.de/informieren/arbeit-und-studium/arbeiten-und-corona/
column74: more generous repayment periods for Corona emergency aid (first program from spring 2020) are now possible. In addition, the repayment of loans (KfW entrepreneur loan, ERP start-up loan with liability exemption, KfW quick loan) remains flexible in the KfW special programme. Thus, the subsequent granting of a second repayment-free year for loans with only one repayment-free start-up year is still unbureaucratically possible and can be applied for via the respective house bank. The scheme, which was originally limited to 31.12.2021, has been extended until 17.06.2022 (application received by KfW). https://archive.vn/xXNzy

column83: Lauterbach announced a change in the testing regulation this week. Among other things, there will continue to be prioritisation for those working in nursing homes and in the medical field. Furthermore, he said, it was planned that all people would also be entitled to PCR retesting after a positive Corona rapid test. In this way, one would have "an efficient, but also safe system" of testing. https://web.archive.org/web/20220211155508/https://www.deutschland.de/en/news/german-federal-government-informs-about-the-corona-crisis

column72: The current short-time allowance regulation expires on 31 March. The Federal Cabinet has therefore initiated [updated] regulations will subsequently apply until 30 June 2022. column115: Due to the situation in the fourth wave, the deplorably high numbers of new cases and deaths and the extremely serious and sometimes even dramatic situation in the healthcare system, the Länder requested the Federal Government to impose a so-called facility-based vaccine mandate as soon as possible: all employees who have contact with vulnerable persons in hospitals and integration assistance facilities as well as in nursing homes, care homes and mobile care services will be required to be vaccinated against the coronavirus. As a result, the Bundestag and Bundesrat passed an amendment to the Infection Protection Act. Employees who work at hospitals, nursing homes and similar institutions must therefore provide proof of being vaccinated against or having recovered from COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20221208111439/https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/coronavirus-vaccination-faq-1959802    Germany’s top court has approved a mandate for health workers to be vaccinated against COVID-19.    The Federal Constitutional Court announced on Thursday that it had rejected complaints against the measure, which came into effect in mid-March.    The court said that the importance of protecting vulnerable people in hospitals and care homes outweighs any infringement of health workers’ rights.    Judges had previously refused to issue an injunction blocking the rules from coming into effect.    Health Minister Karl Lauterbach welcomed Thursday’s ruling, saying that “the state is obliged to protect vulnerable groups.”    https://web.archive.org/web/20221208174126/https://www.euronews.com/2022/05/19/germany-s-top-court-approves-vaccine-mandate-for-health-workers    On 27 April 2022, the German Constitutional Court rejected challenges to the vaccine mandate for healthcare workers (case reference: 1 BvR 2649/21).    The case concerned the obligation for professionals working in the healthcare system to provide a vaccine or recovery certificate to attend work. The challenged rule applied not only to medical or nurse employees, but also to the administrative, cleaning or kitchen staff, if they are employed by a healthcare facility. From 15 March 2022, the absence of a vaccine or recovery certificate prevents employees from entering the employers's premises and to exercise their professional activity.    The claimants had alleged an infringement to the bodily integrity and to the right to exercise a profession. However, the court rejected the claim, holding that the interference with the right of bodily integrity is justified because the legislators pursued a legitimate scope to protect vulnerable groups from COVID-19 infection.    About the encroachment of the right to exercise a profession, the court distinguished between medical and nursing staff from other kind of employees: the former are obliged to provide a proof of vaccination as a prerequisite, in order to exercise their professional activity. The latter are required to provide the vaccination or recovered certificate because they come into contact with medical and nursing staff and indirectly with vulnerable groups.    The court also mentioned the sentence of the challenged provision authorising the ban to enter the employers' premises or from working there, if the healthcare staff does not comply with the vaccine mandate. This ban gives rise to a separate interference with occupational freedom. However, the court again relied on the argument that this interference is justified to protect vulnerable groups.    https://web.archive.org/web/20221201192147/https://www.covid19litigation.org/news/2022/05/germany-healthcare-workers-vaccine-mandates-justified-constitutional-court-holds

column10: Changed Infection Protection Act: The corona rules will largely be abolished in the future. Basic protection such as the obligation to wear masks, for example in hospitals or care facilities, can remain in place. The obligation to wear masks in local public transport and the obligation to carry out tests in schools are still possible. The regulation in the respective federal state is decisive . In air and long-distance passenger transport, the mask requirement remains in place nationwide. At the same time , stricter, locally limited regulations    https://archive.ph/g4JrB

column37: https://archive.ph/xul1r translated by google translate from the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung:  In North Rhine-Westphalia, the outdoor pool season starts in many places without strict corona rules. "Since basically almost all corona measures in North Rhine-Westphalia are history, can also be assumed of an outdoor pool operation as before the pandemic," said a spokeswoman for the German Society for bathing in Essen. However, bathroom operators could continue to decide for themselves by domiciliary right whether the 2G or 3G rule applies. Many outdoor swimming pools want to open on 1 May.

column10: https://archive.ph/Qih68  google translate:Despite high numbers of corona infections, most corona rules in schools have expired. This is what the Infection Protection Act provides. Distance rules and mask requirements at schools no longer apply. Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and Hamburg were initially an exception because they made use of the hotspot regulation. In the meantime, however, the mask requirement has also been completely omitted here. The corona test obligation also no longer exists in most federal states. In this news blog, the school portal informs about what the relaxation in the federal states looks like in concrete terms and how the abolition of the mask requirement and other measures affects the infection situation in schools.

column101: Due to the situation in the fourth wave, the deplorably high numbers of new cases and deaths and the extremely serious and sometimes even dramatic situation in the healthcare system, the Länder requested the Federal Government to impose a so-called facility-based vaccine mandate as soon as possible: all employees who have contact with vulnerable persons in hospitals and integration assistance facilities as well as in nursing homes, care homes and mobile care services will be required to be vaccinated against the coronavirus. As a result, the Bundestag and Bundesrat passed an amendment to the Infection Protection Act. Employees who work at hospitals, nursing homes and similar institutions must therefore provide proof of being vaccinated against or having recovered from COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20221208111439/https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/coronavirus-vaccination-faq-1959802    Germany’s top court has approved a mandate for health workers to be vaccinated against COVID-19.    The Federal Constitutional Court announced on Thursday that it had rejected complaints against the measure, which came into effect in mid-March.    The court said that the importance of protecting vulnerable people in hospitals and care homes outweighs any infringement of health workers’ rights.    Judges had previously refused to issue an injunction blocking the rules from coming into effect.    Health Minister Karl Lauterbach welcomed Thursday’s ruling, saying that “the state is obliged to protect vulnerable groups.”    https://web.archive.org/web/20221208174126/https://www.euronews.com/2022/05/19/germany-s-top-court-approves-vaccine-mandate-for-health-workers    On 27 April 2022, the German Constitutional Court rejected challenges to the vaccine mandate for healthcare workers (case reference: 1 BvR 2649/21).    The case concerned the obligation for professionals working in the healthcare system to provide a vaccine or recovery certificate to attend work. The challenged rule applied not only to medical or nurse employees, but also to the administrative, cleaning or kitchen staff, if they are employed by a healthcare facility. From 15 March 2022, the absence of a vaccine or recovery certificate prevents employees from entering the employers's premises and to exercise their professional activity.    The claimants had alleged an infringement to the bodily integrity and to the right to exercise a profession. However, the court rejected the claim, holding that the interference with the right of bodily integrity is justified because the legislators pursued a legitimate scope to protect vulnerable groups from COVID-19 infection.    About the encroachment of the right to exercise a profession, the court distinguished between medical and nursing staff from other kind of employees: the former are obliged to provide a proof of vaccination as a prerequisite, in order to exercise their professional activity. The latter are required to provide the vaccination or recovered certificate because they come into contact with medical and nursing staff and indirectly with vulnerable groups.    The court also mentioned the sentence of the challenged provision authorising the ban to enter the employers' premises or from working there, if the healthcare staff does not comply with the vaccine mandate. This ban gives rise to a separate interference with occupational freedom. However, the court again relied on the argument that this interference is justified to protect vulnerable groups.    https://web.archive.org/web/20221201192147/https://www.covid19litigation.org/news/2022/05/germany-healthcare-workers-vaccine-mandates-justified-constitutional-court-holds

column19: Translated from the link provided below by google translate:  "In principle, the 3-G obligation to provide proof when entering the workplace has been omitted."    However, this does not change the fact that the institution-related vaccination obligation has been in force for employees in health and care facilities since 16 March 2022. So you have to keep the proof of vaccination.    The home office obligation is omitted.  Companies are now increasingly obliged to assess the risk situation themselves and to define protective measures in operational hygiene concepts – together with the works or staff council.    The employer only has to offer one self-test per week.    The following applies unchanged: keep your distance, observe hygiene, wear a mask and ventilate regularly.    https://archive.ph/KwvlS

column110: https://archive.ph/xFAaV  Screening in hospitals introduced 1st of October 2022  Recommended 2nd booster:  All people aged 60 and over;  Persons aged 5 years and older with an increased risk of severe COVID-19 due to an underlying disease, in particular immunodeficiency (note: since the new bivalent vaccines adapted to the Omikron variants are only approved from the age of twelve, only the previous monovalent vaccines approved for this age group should be used for 5-11 year olds); people living in care institutions or persons with an increased risk of a severe course of illness in integration support institutions;  People who work in medical institutions or care – especially if they have direct contact with the vulnerable people entrusted to them.  For all these people, the second booster should be given six months after the first booster dose or SARS-CoV-2 infection.
